const CH=[
{id:"preface",n:0,t:"Preface",ic:"◈",cl:"#8b4513",ss:[{id:"pre",t:"About This Textbook",c:`Artificial intelligence has, since its inception, been animated by two fundamentally different visions of how machines might think.\n\nOne vision, rooted in the **symbolic tradition** of Turing, McCarthy, Newell, and Simon, holds that intelligence is the manipulation of symbols according to formal rules — that thinking is computation over structured representations, that knowledge can be explicitly encoded in logical formalisms, and that reasoning proceeds by deduction, induction, and abduction over those representations.\n\nThe other vision, rooted in the **connectionist tradition** of Rosenblatt, Rumelhart, and Hinton, holds that intelligence emerges from the statistical properties of vast networks of simple processing units — that knowledge is implicit in the weights of connections, that learning proceeds by gradient-based optimization, and that representation is distributed rather than symbolic.\n\nFor decades, these two traditions developed largely in isolation. Symbolic AI excelled at logical reasoning, planning, and knowledge representation but struggled with perception and learning from raw data. Connectionist AI excelled at pattern recognition and learning from massive datasets but struggled with systematic generalization, compositional reasoning, explainability, and operating with limited data.\n\n**Neuro-symbolic AI** represents the convergence of these two paradigms into hybrid architectures that aspire to combine the learning efficiency and perceptual power of neural networks with the reasoning rigor, explainability, and knowledge representation capabilities of symbolic AI. This convergence addresses the most pressing practical limitations of contemporary AI: LLMs hallucinate because they lack grounded symbolic knowledge; deep learning classifiers fail to generalize systematically because they lack compositional structure; black-box models cannot be deployed in high-stakes domains because they lack interpretable reasoning traces.\n\nThis textbook provides a comprehensive treatment of the theoretical foundations, architectural paradigms, landmark systems, and application domains of neuro-symbolic AI, drawing on the 2025 systematic review of 167 papers by Colelough and Regli, comprehensive surveys by Garcez and Lamb, and landmark system descriptions from DeepMind, MIT-IBM, and other leading laboratories.`}]},

{id:"ch1",n:1,t:"Historical Foundations & Philosophical Context",ic:"I",cl:"#7c3aed",ss:[
{id:"1.1",t:"The Symbolic Tradition: Logic Theorist to Expert Systems",c:`The symbolic tradition traces to the **1956 Dartmouth Conference**, where McCarthy, Minsky, Rochester, and Shannon coined "artificial intelligence" and articulated the hypothesis that "every aspect of learning or any other feature of intelligence can in principle be so precisely described that a machine can be made to simulate it."\n\nThe earliest programs — Newell and Simon's **Logic Theorist** (1956) and **General Problem Solver** (1957) — manipulated symbolic representations according to formal rules. The approach reached commercial zenith in the 1980s with **expert systems**: **MYCIN** (infectious disease diagnosis), **DENDRAL** (chemical analysis), **R1/XCON** (computer configuration). These encoded domain knowledge as production rules, achieving expert-level performance in narrow domains.\n\nHowever, the **knowledge acquisition bottleneck** — the laborious process of extracting and encoding expert knowledge — severely limited scalability. Expert systems were **brittle**: performing well within their knowledge base but failing catastrophically at boundaries, lacking the ability to learn from experience, and unable to handle perceptual richness.\n\nDespite limitations, the symbolic tradition contributed foundational concepts essential to neuro-symbolic AI: formal **knowledge representation** (ontologies, frames, semantic networks), **logical inference** (deduction, abduction, default reasoning), **planning** (STRIPS, partial-order planning), and the explicit **separation of knowledge from inference** — the principle that what a system knows should be representable independently of how it uses that knowledge.`,kt:["Dartmouth Conference","Logic Theorist","Expert Systems","MYCIN","DENDRAL","Knowledge Acquisition Bottleneck"],ins:"The knowledge acquisition bottleneck of the 1980s foreshadows today's knowledge engineering bottleneck in neuro-symbolic AI — the difficulty of creating symbolic rules that pair with neural components."},
{id:"1.2",t:"The Connectionist Tradition: Perceptrons to Deep Learning",c:`The connectionist tradition began with Rosenblatt's **perceptron** (1958) and McCulloch-Pitts' formal neuron (1943), but was sidelined by Minsky and Papert's **1969 critique**. Resurgence came with **backpropagation** (Rumelhart, Hinton, Williams, 1986).\n\nThe **deep learning revolution** of the 2010s — driven by large datasets, GPU computing, and innovations including **CNNs** (LeCun, 1998), **LSTMs** (Hochreiter & Schmidhuber, 1997), and the **transformer** (Vaswani et al., 2017) — achieved superhuman perception and near-human NLP. The GPT family, BERT, and successors showed language models trained on massive corpora could exhibit remarkable linguistic competence.\n\nYet limitations became equally apparent: neural networks are **data-hungry** (requiring orders of magnitude more examples than humans), lack **systematic compositionality** (the ability to combine known concepts in novel ways), are vulnerable to **adversarial attacks** (exploiting statistical rather than semantic representations), **hallucinate** (generating plausible but factually incorrect output), and are fundamentally **opaque** (explaining why a network produced a particular output is unsolved in general).\n\nThese limitations motivated the resurgence of interest in hybrid neuro-symbolic approaches.`,kt:["Perceptron","Backpropagation","CNN","LSTM","Transformer","Hallucination","Adversarial Attacks"],dg:"timeline"},
{id:"1.3",t:"Kahneman's Dual-Process Theory and the AI Parallel",c:`Daniel Kahneman's **dual-process theory** (*Thinking, Fast and Slow*, 2011) provides a powerful conceptual framework:\n\n**System 1** — Fast, automatic, intuitive, unconscious, parallel. Handles pattern recognition, perception, rapid responses. It is effortless, always on, and operates below conscious awareness.\n\n**System 2** — Slow, deliberate, analytical, conscious, sequential. Handles logical reasoning, planning, complex calculation. It requires effort, is capacity-limited, and is experienced as concentration.\n\nThe AI parallel is striking: **Neural networks model System 1** — excelling at rapid pattern recognition but operating opaquely. **Symbolic AI models System 2** — excelling at deliberate reasoning but lacking perceptual fluidity. Neuro-symbolic AI aspires to **integrate both**, achieving perceptual fluency and reasoning rigor — just as human cognition seamlessly combines fast intuition with slow deliberation.\n\nBengio's **NeurIPS 2019 keynote** on System 2 deep learning argued the field must develop architectures capable of compositional, causal, and abstract reasoning — capabilities requiring symbolic structure — catalyzing the neuro-symbolic research program.`,kt:["System 1","System 2","Dual-Process Theory","Kahneman","Bengio NeurIPS 2019"],dg:"dualprocess",ins:"The dual-process metaphor provides design guidance: assign perception and rapid classification to neural modules (System 1) and verification, planning, and constraint enforcement to symbolic modules (System 2)."},
{id:"1.4",t:"Gary Marcus and the Case for Hybrid Architecture",c:`**Gary Marcus** argues robust AI requires "the triumvirate of **hybrid architecture, rich prior knowledge, and sophisticated techniques for reasoning**" (*Rebooting AI*, 2019, with Ernest Davis). He contends "we cannot construct rich cognitive models in an adequate, automated way without" the machinery of symbol manipulation.\n\nThis is contested by the **"bitter lesson"** (Richard Sutton, 2019): methods leveraging massive computation historically outperform those relying on human-crafted knowledge.\n\nThe practical evidence increasingly supports a **middle ground**: the most successful systems — AlphaGeometry, tool-augmented LLMs — explicitly combine neural and symbolic components. The question is not whether to combine, but **how tightly to couple them** and which architectural pattern best serves a given domain.`,kt:["Marcus","Rebooting AI","Bitter Lesson","Sutton","Hybrid Architecture","Emergence"]}
],rf:["Bengio (2019). System 1→System 2 deep learning. NeurIPS Keynote.","Kahneman (2011). Thinking, Fast and Slow. FSG.","Marcus & Davis (2019). Rebooting AI. Pantheon.","McCarthy (1960). Programs with common sense.","Minsky & Papert (1969). Perceptrons. MIT Press.","Newell & Simon (1976). Computer science as empirical inquiry. CACM.","Rumelhart, Hinton, Williams (1986). Backpropagation. Nature, 323.","Sutton (2019). The bitter lesson.","Vaswani et al. (2017). Attention is all you need. NeurIPS."]},

{id:"ch2",n:2,t:"Taxonomies of Neuro-Symbolic Integration",ic:"II",cl:"#be185d",ss:[
{id:"2.1",t:"Kautz's Taxonomy of Neuro-Symbolic Architectures",c:`Henry Kautz's **2020 AAAI Engelmore Memorial Lecture** identified six architectural patterns arranged from loose to tight coupling:\n\n**Type 1 — Symbolic Neuro Symbolic.** Neural replaces symbolic entirely. Example: neural NLP parser replacing rule-based parser.\n\n**Type 2 — Symbolic[Neuro].** Symbolic system with neural subroutine. Example: **AlphaGo** — Monte Carlo tree search (symbolic) uses neural network for position evaluation.\n\n**Type 3 — Neuro | Symbolic.** Neural model distilled from symbolic rules, or symbolic rules extracted from trained neural network. Includes knowledge distillation and rule extraction.\n\n**Type 4 — Neuro: Symbolic → Neuro.** Symbolic system generates training data for neural network. Example: **AlphaGeometry** — symbolic engine generates 100M synthetic theorem-proof pairs to train a neural language model.\n\n**Type 5 — Neuro[Symbolic].** Neural network contains an embedded symbolic reasoning engine. Logic operates within the neural computation graph. Examples: **Neural Theorem Provers**, **Logic Tensor Networks**, where logical inference rules are encoded as differentiable operations.\n\n**Type 6 — Neuro ↔ Symbolic** (full System 1/System 2 integration). Neural and symbolic operate in tightly coupled feedback loop, each informing the other. Most ambitious pattern — the architectural gold standard.`,kt:["Kautz Taxonomy","Type 1–6","Loose Coupling","Tight Coupling","AAAI 2020"],dg:"kautz",ins:"Most production systems today operate at Type 2–4. True Type 6 integration — seamless bidirectional feedback — remains largely aspirational."},
{id:"2.2",t:"Functional Classification: Learning for Reasoning vs. Reasoning for Learning",c:`An alternative classification by functional role (Sarker et al., 2021; Wan et al., 2024):\n\n**Learning for Reasoning:** Neural modules process unstructured data → produce structured symbolic representations → symbolic reasoning engine reasons over them. Neural serves symbolic by providing perceptual grounding. **NSCL** exemplifies: neural perception extracts object properties from images; symbolic program executor reasons over them to answer compositional questions.\n\n**Reasoning for Learning:** Symbolic knowledge constrains, guides, or regularizes neural learning. Prior knowledge in logical form is injected into training, improving sample efficiency and generalization. **Semantic loss functions** (penalizing constraint-violating outputs) and **DeepProbLog** (logical structure frames neural predictions) exemplify this.\n\n**Hybrid Loop:** The most sophisticated architectures feature **bidirectional** interaction: neural modules learn better symbolic representations from reasoner feedback; symbolic reasoner adapts queries based on neural outputs. This creates a **virtuous cycle** — hallmark of the most advanced neuro-symbolic systems.\n\nThis functional classification cuts across Kautz's taxonomy: a Type 2 system could implement either direction depending on information flow. The classifications are complementary lenses for understanding the design space.`,kt:["Learning for Reasoning","Reasoning for Learning","Hybrid Loop","NSCL","Semantic Loss"],dg:"functional"},
{id:"2.3",t:"The 2025 Systematic Review: Quantitative Landscape",c:`Colelough and Regli's **2025 systematic review** (NeSy@IJCAI) analyzed **167 peer-reviewed papers** (2020–2024), selected from 1,428 via PRISMA methodology. Five research areas mapped:\n\n**Learning & Inference: 63% of papers** (~105). Dominant focus: end-to-end differentiable reasoning, dynamic multi-source knowledge reasoning, neural-symbolic integration for enhanced learning.\n\n**Knowledge Representation: 44%** (~73). Structured representations bridging paradigms: knowledge graphs, ontologies, hybrid embeddings.\n\n**Logic & Reasoning: 35%** (~58). Integrating logic-based methods with neural networks: logical and probabilistic reasoning, syntax and semantics of NeSy systems.\n\n**Explainability & Trustworthiness: 28%** (~47). Creating interpretable models and reasoning processes. Notably **underrepresented** relative to its importance for deployment.\n\n**Meta-Cognition: 5%** (~8). System's capacity to monitor, evaluate, and adjust its own reasoning. Least explored — a **critical frontier** for self-aware AI.\n\n**AlphaGeometry** was the only system intersecting all four primary areas — underscoring both its sophistication and the rarity of comprehensive NeSy systems. The review noted pronounced concentration on CV and NLP, with healthcare, robotics, and scientific reasoning underrepresented.`,kt:["Systematic Review","PRISMA","167 Papers","Research Distribution","NeSy@IJCAI"],dg:"research_areas"}
],rf:["Colelough & Regli (2025). Systematic review. arXiv:2501.05435.","Kautz (2020). The third AI summer. AAAI Lecture.","Mao et al. (2019). NSCL. ICLR.","Sarker et al. (2021). NeSy: Current trends. AI Comms.","Wan et al. (2024). Survey on neurosymbolic approaches. arXiv."]},

{id:"ch3",n:3,t:"Core Frameworks & Landmark Systems",ic:"III",cl:"#b45309",ss:[
{id:"3.1",t:"DeepProbLog: Neural Probabilistic Logic Programming",c:`**DeepProbLog** (Manhaeve et al., NeurIPS 2018) extends ProbLog with **neural predicates** — predicates whose truth values are determined by neural network output rather than logical derivation. This enables end-to-end differentiable training combining neural perception with probabilistic logical reasoning.\n\nA probabilistic logic program defines the structure of the problem, specifying how concepts relate through logical rules. Neural networks provide the perceptual grounding: given an image, a neural classifier predicts the probability of each possible digit. These probabilities feed into the logic program, which reasons about relationships between perceived entities.\n\nThe entire system trains **end-to-end** by backpropagating through both the logic program (using the gradient of the **weighted model count** with respect to neural network parameters) and the neural networks. The key innovation: computing gradients through logical inference, differentiating through the probability of a logical query — a combinatorial operation made tractable through **algebraic circuit compilation** (specifically, compilation to **d-DNNF** — Deterministic Decomposable Negation Normal Form).\n\nApplied to handwritten arithmetic, probabilistic program induction, and multi-task learning with logical constraints.`,kt:["DeepProbLog","Neural Predicates","ProbLog","Weighted Model Count","Algebraic Circuits","d-DNNF"],ins:"DeepProbLog's core innovation — differentiating through logical inference via algebraic circuits — solved the technical problem blocking neuro-symbolic integration: how to send gradient signals from symbolic reasoning back to neural parameters."},
{id:"3.2",t:"Logic Tensor Networks (LTNs)",c:`**Logic Tensor Networks** (Badreddine, Garcez, Serafini, Spranger; Artificial Intelligence 2022) encode first-order logic in neural tensor networks using **real-valued (fuzzy) logic** semantics.\n\nVariables range over **vectors** (tensor representations). **Predicates and functions** are implemented as neural networks. **Logical connectives** (AND, OR, NOT, IMPLIES) are implemented as differentiable fuzzy logic operations (t-norms and t-conorms). Truth values are real numbers in [0, 1].\n\nThis grounding enables integrating logical background knowledge directly into the neural network's **loss function**. Training maximizes the **"satisfaction"** of logical axioms: neural weights are optimized so predictions make logical constraints as close to true as possible. The user specifies *what must be true* (as axioms); the system learns *how to make it true* (by adjusting weights).\n\nApplied to **semantic image interpretation** (learning to classify objects while respecting logical constraints about relationships), **knowledge graph completion**, and **ontology learning**. Key advantage: learning from both labeled examples and logical constraints simultaneously — enabling **semi-supervised** learning where labeled data is scarce but domain knowledge is available.`,kt:["Logic Tensor Networks","Fuzzy Logic","t-norms","Satisfaction","Grounding","Semi-supervised"]},
{id:"3.3",t:"AlphaGeometry: The Landmark System",c:`**AlphaGeometry** (Trinh, Wu, Le, He, Luong; Nature 2024) solves Euclidean plane geometry at **International Mathematical Olympiad (IMO) gold medalist level**. Its architecture is a textbook example of Kautz's Type 4/Type 6 neuro-symbolic integration:\n\n**Symbolic component:** Formal deduction engine (**DD+AR** — Deductive Database with Algebraic Rules). Applies known geometric theorems systematically. Every step is verifiable and logically sound. But the search space for proofs is **combinatorially explosive**.\n\n**Neural component:** A language model trained on **100 million synthetic theorem-proof pairs** generated by the symbolic engine. Its role: suggest **auxiliary constructions** — adding new geometric elements (points, lines, circles) that may unlock a proof. When the symbolic engine reaches a dead end, the neural model proposes candidate constructions.\n\n**The key insight:** The symbolic engine ensures **logical rigor** but cannot navigate the vast search space alone; the neural model provides intuitive **"creative leaps"** suggesting fruitful constructions but cannot guarantee correctness. Together they achieve what neither could alone.\n\nColelough and Regli's review identified AlphaGeometry as the **only system intersecting all four primary research areas** — learning and inference, knowledge representation, logic and reasoning, and explainability.`,kt:["AlphaGeometry","IMO","DD+AR","Auxiliary Constructions","100M Synthetic Pairs","Nature 2024"],dg:"alphageometry"},
{id:"3.4",t:"Neuro-Symbolic Concept Learner (NSCL)",c:`The **NSCL** (Mao, Gan, Kohli, Tenenbaum, Wu; MIT-IBM, ICLR 2019) integrates neural perception with symbolic program execution for **visual question answering**. Three components:\n\n**Neural perception module** — extracts object-level representations from images (shape, color, size, material).\n**Semantic parser** — converts natural language questions into symbolic programs.\n**Symbolic program executor** — evaluates programs over extracted representations.\n\nKey strength: **sample efficiency**. Because symbolic reasoning provides strong structural inductive biases, NSCL learns from far fewer examples than end-to-end approaches. It maintains accuracy with as little as **10% of the data** end-to-end models require, and demonstrates superior **out-of-distribution generalization** because compositional program structure ensures novel concept combinations are handled correctly.\n\nThe architectural lesson: by enforcing compositional structure through symbolic programs, the system achieves **systematic generalization** that pure neural approaches consistently fail to achieve.`,kt:["NSCL","VQA","Sample Efficiency","Compositional Generalization","MIT-IBM","10% Data"]},
{id:"3.5",t:"Scallop: Differentiable Reasoning at Scale",c:`**Scallop** (Li, Huang, Naik, Xie; UPenn, PLDI 2023) is a scalable neuro-symbolic programming language based on **Datalog with provenance semirings**. It supports **top-k proofs provenance**, enabling efficient differentiable reasoning over potentially exponential search spaces.\n\nApplied to challenging tasks including VQA on CLEVR, hand-written formula evaluation, and path planning — demonstrating NeSy reasoning can scale to complex problems with competitive performance.\n\nScallop's significance: it demonstrates that the scalability bottleneck in neuro-symbolic AI is not insurmountable. By using algebraic structures to efficiently track and differentiate through proof paths, it achieves practical performance on tasks previously considered too large for exact neuro-symbolic reasoning.`,kt:["Scallop","Datalog","Provenance Semirings","PLDI 2023","Top-k Proofs"]},
{id:"3.6",t:"The DeepLog Machine & Unified Frameworks",c:`The proliferation of frameworks — DeepProbLog, NeurASP, Scallop, LTNs, Semantic Loss — created a need for **unifying theoretical frameworks**.\n\nThe **DeepLog Machine** (Derkinderen, Manhaeve, De Raedt; 2025) introduces an intermediate language based on **algebraic structures** (Boolean, probabilistic, fuzzy) that can express multiple NeSy frameworks' semantics. It makes explicit the algebraic structure in which logical and probabilistic reasoning is interpreted.\n\nTransitioning between frameworks requires only replacing the algebraic structure — e.g., from DeepProbLog to fuzzy logic requires swapping Boolean for t-norm-based fuzzy structure while keeping everything else unchanged. The framework compiles into **algebraic circuits** directly usable for learning and inference.\n\nThis unification enables **systematic comparison** of different approaches and facilitates theoretical analysis of when each approach is most appropriate.`,kt:["DeepLog Machine","Algebraic Structures","Unification","Algebraic Circuits"],dg:"frameworks_comparison"}
],rf:["Badreddine et al. (2022). LTN. Artificial Intelligence, 303.","Derkinderen et al. (2025). DeepLog Machine. arXiv:2508.13697.","Li et al. (2023). Scallop. PLDI.","Manhaeve et al. (2018). DeepProbLog. NeurIPS.","Mao et al. (2019). NSCL. ICLR.","Trinh et al. (2024). AlphaGeometry. Nature, 625, 476–482."]},

{id:"ch4",n:4,t:"Neural Networks with Symbolic Reasoning",ic:"IV",cl:"#047857",ss:[
{id:"4.1",t:"Differentiable Logic and Fuzzy Relaxation",c:`The central challenge: bridging the **representational gap** between continuous, differentiable neural space and discrete, non-differentiable symbolic logic. Neural networks require differentiable operations for gradient-based optimization; logical operations (AND, OR, NOT) are inherently discrete.\n\n**Fuzzy logic** provides the most established framework for this relaxation. Truth values become real numbers in [0, 1]. Logical connectives are implemented through **t-norms** (conjunction), **t-conorms** (disjunction), and negation operators:\n\n**Product t-norm:** AND(a, b) = a × b — smoothest gradients, multiplicative interaction. Can suffer vanishing gradients in deep logical chains.\n\n**Gödel t-norm:** AND(a, b) = min(a, b) — preserves "weakest link" semantics. Zero gradients for the non-minimum argument.\n\n**Łukasiewicz t-norm:** AND(a, b) = max(0, a + b − 1) — additive, allows contradiction tolerance useful in noisy real-world settings.\n\nEach choice induces different gradient behavior with implications for learning dynamics. LTNs use this fuzzy relaxation so that axiom satisfaction becomes a **differentiable function** of network parameters, enabling training by gradient descent to maximize truth of background knowledge while minimizing prediction error.`,kt:["Differentiable Logic","Fuzzy Logic","t-norms","t-conorms","Representational Gap","Gradient Flow"],dg:"tnorms"},
{id:"4.2",t:"Semantic Loss Functions",c:`**Semantic loss** adds a penalty measuring the degree to which neural outputs **violate specified logical constraints**. The Pseudo-Semantic Loss integrates logic within the loss function for autoregressive models.\n\nThis approach is **architecturally non-invasive**: only the loss changes; the neural architecture remains unmodified. Applicable to existing deep learning pipelines. The trade-off: constraints influence learning only **indirectly** (through loss gradient) rather than being embedded in computation.\n\nEmprically shown to improve generalization and reduce constraint violations, particularly in **low-data regimes** where logical inductive bias compensates for limited training examples — particularly relevant for healthcare, where labeled data is expensive and domain constraints are well-understood.\n\nThe **integration depth spectrum**: Semantic Loss (lightest — only loss changes) → LTNs (medium — logic shapes computation) → DeepProbLog/LNNs (deepest — logic IS the computation). The right choice depends on requirements for interpretability, constraint strength, and architectural flexibility.`,kt:["Semantic Loss","Constraint Violation","Inductive Bias","Non-Invasive","Integration Depth"],ins:"Semantic loss functions are the entry-level approach to neuro-symbolic integration — add to any existing neural network without architectural changes. Ideal for incrementally improving production systems.",dg:"depth_spectrum"},
{id:"4.3",t:"Neural Theorem Provers (NTPs)",c:`**NTPs** (Rocktäschel & Riedel, NeurIPS 2017) construct neural networks from **AND-OR proof trees** generated from knowledge base rules. Given a query, the NTP generates all possible proof paths, computes a **soft proof score** for each, and aggregates into a final confidence.\n\nThe knowledge base contains known facts (truth value 1) and **neural predicates** (computed by neural networks) — enabling learning missing facts from data while reasoning using logical rules.\n\nApplied to knowledge base completion, link prediction, multi-hop reasoning. Main limitation: **scalability** — proof paths grow exponentially with reasoning depth. Approximate methods and **attention-based pruning** address this.\n\nNTPs illustrate a fundamental tension: the expressiveness of the symbolic component (deeper reasoning, more complete proofs) directly conflicts with computational tractability. Managing this tension is a recurring theme across the field.`,kt:["Neural Theorem Provers","AND-OR Proof Trees","Soft Proof Score","Multi-hop Reasoning","Scalability"]},
{id:"4.4",t:"Logical Neural Networks (LNNs)",c:`IBM's **Logical Neural Networks** (Riegel, Gray et al., 2020) represent a fundamentally different approach. Every neuron corresponds to a component of a logical formula, and the network's **architecture is isomorphic to the logical structure** of the knowledge base. Activation functions implement real-valued logic preserving **soundness and completeness** while being fully differentiable.\n\nA distinctive feature: **bidirectional reasoning** — both upward inference (computing conclusion truth from premises) AND **downward inference** (computing required premise truth given a conclusion). This enables answering "Is X true?" AND "What would need to be true for X to hold?" — essential for explanation and counterfactual reasoning.\n\nApplied to NLI, knowledge base reasoning, and notably for healthcare: a 2024 study demonstrated LNN-based **diabetes prediction** outperforming Random Forest and SVM while providing **interpretable insights** into which features (glucose, BMI) contributed to each prediction. The learned weights provided a **transparent, auditable diagnostic reasoning path** — bridging accuracy and explainability critical for clinical deployment.`,kt:["Logical Neural Networks","Bidirectional Reasoning","IBM","Isomorphic Architecture","Upward/Downward Inference"],dg:"lnn"}
],rf:["Badreddine et al. (2022). LTN. AI, 303.","Riegel et al. (2020). LNN. arXiv:2006.13155.","Rocktäschel & Riedel (2017). Differentiable proving. NeurIPS.","Xu et al. (2018). Semantic loss. ICML."]},

{id:"ch5",n:5,t:"Neuro-Symbolic AI & Large Language Models",ic:"V",cl:"#1d4ed8",ss:[
{id:"5.1",t:"The Hallucination Problem",c:`LLMs model the **probability distribution of the next token** given preceding context, without any mechanism for verifying factual accuracy. In high-stakes domains (medicine, law, science), **hallucination is a deal-breaker**: a medical LLM recommending a non-existent drug poses direct safety risk; a legal LLM fabricating case citations undermines legal argumentation.\n\nNeuro-symbolic approaches offer principled solutions: **grounding** LLM outputs in structured knowledge bases (knowledge graphs, ontologies, databases) and **verifying** through symbolic reasoning (logical inference, constraint checking, formal verification). NeSy adoption increased significantly in 2025 specifically to address hallucination, with Amazon and other major companies reportedly applying neuro-symbolic methods to production systems.`,kt:["Hallucination","Factual Grounding","Symbolic Verification","Token Prediction"]},
{id:"5.2",t:"LLM-Symbolic Solver (LLM-SS) Architectures",c:`**LLM-Symbolic Solver (LLM-SS)** represents the dominant hybrid pattern: LLM as natural language interface and reasoning guide (**System 1**); separate symbolic solver provides rigorous, verifiable computation (**System 2**). The LLM translates queries into formal representations; the solver computes answers; the LLM translates back.\n\nChen et al. (NeSy@IJCAI 2025) demonstrated advantages over integrative approaches:\n\n**(1) Interpretable reasoning chain** — each symbolic step independently verifiable, providing genuine audit trail rather than post-hoc rationalization.\n\n**(2) Retains LLM capabilities** — language understanding, generation, in-context learning remain fully available; symbolic solver adds capability without removing any.\n\n**(3) Modular and model-agnostic** — LLM and solver upgraded independently. Better LLM swaps in without retraining symbolic component.\n\nThe framework is **modular by design, model-agnostic, and domain-agnostic** — providing a template for building LLM-SS systems across diverse application domains.`,kt:["LLM-SS","Modular Architecture","Model-Agnostic","Interpretable Reasoning Chain"],dg:"llm_ss"},
{id:"5.3",t:"Tool-Augmented LLMs as Neuro-Symbolic Systems",c:`Augmenting LLMs with external tools — calculators, code interpreters, search engines, formal reasoning engines — is a **pragmatic neuro-symbolic integration**. Systems like ChatGPT with Code Interpreter or Toolformer use the LLM as a natural language interface determining when to invoke tools, what input to provide, and how to interpret results.\n\nFrom a neuro-symbolic perspective, each tool invocation **transfers a subtask from the neural (statistical) to the symbolic (formal) domain**. The LLM handles language understanding and decides what computation is needed; the tool performs computation with formal guarantees.\n\nFang et al. (AAAI 2024) demonstrated LLMs can function as **neuro-symbolic reasoners** when augmented with symbolic tools, achieving superior performance on logical, mathematical, and commonsense reasoning. Even a **loosely-coupled tool-augmented approach** substantially improves reasoning reliability.\n\nPractical implication: organizations can achieve neuro-symbolic benefits by **augmenting existing LLM deployments** rather than building new architectures.`,kt:["Tool Augmentation","Toolformer","Code Interpreter","Loose Coupling","Pragmatic NeSy"]},
{id:"5.4",t:"Knowledge Graph Augmentation for Grounded Generation",c:`**Knowledge graph-augmented generation** combines LLM fluency with factual grounding. **DR.KNOWS** (Gao et al., JMIR AI, 2025) retrieves contextually relevant paths from **UMLS-based knowledge graphs** to augment LLM diagnostic reasoning, reducing hallucination by anchoring output in verified medical knowledge.\n\nPan et al. (IEEE TKDE, 2024) provided a roadmap for unifying LLMs and knowledge graphs, identifying three integration patterns: **KG-enhanced LLMs** (graph structure improves reasoning), **LLM-augmented KGs** (LLMs construct/complete knowledge graphs), and **synergized LLM+KG** (bidirectional enhancement) — the most mature neuro-symbolic integration.`,kt:["DR.KNOWS","Knowledge Graphs","UMLS","KG-LLM Synergy","Pan et al."]},
{id:"5.5",t:"Neuro-Symbolic Generative AI for Explainable Reasoning",c:`A 2025 study (Int. J. Science and Research Archive) developed a hybrid combining **GPT-NeoX** with a symbolic reasoning engine (rule-based logic interpreter + knowledge graph). Results:\n\nThe hybrid achieved **93.1% logical reasoning accuracy**, outperforming GPT-3 (79.5%) and SymbolicGPT (88.7%). Generated explanations aligned with symbolic traces in **91.2% of test cases** (verified by human annotation). In NLI tasks, the hybrid demonstrated **17% improvement** in explanation fidelity over purely neural baselines.\n\nThis provides concrete empirical evidence that neuro-symbolic integration improves both accuracy and interpretability in generative settings.`,kt:["93.1% Accuracy","GPT-NeoX","Explanation Fidelity","91.2% Alignment","17% Improvement"]}
],rf:["Chen (2025). Comparative study. NeSy@IJCAI. PMLR 284.","Fang et al. (2024). LLMs as NeSy reasoners. AAAI.","Gao et al. (2025). KG-augmented LLMs. JMIR AI, 4.","Pan et al. (2024). Unifying LLMs and KGs. IEEE TKDE, 36(7).","Patil & Jadon (2025). NeSy generative AI. IJSRA, 16(01).","Schick et al. (2024). Toolformer. NeurIPS 2023."]},

{id:"ch6",n:6,t:"Robustness, Uncertainty & Trustworthiness",ic:"VI",cl:"#dc2626",ss:[
{id:"6.1",t:"The Trust Deficit in Pure Neural AI",c:`High-stakes deployment (healthcare, autonomous vehicles, finance, criminal justice) requires guarantees purely neural systems cannot provide. Vulnerabilities: **adversarial attacks** (small, imperceptible input perturbations causing dramatic output changes), **distribution shift** (degraded performance when deployment differs from training), **catastrophic forgetting** (loss of previous knowledge when trained on new tasks).\n\nThese stem from the statistical nature of neural representations. Neural diagnostic systems are sensitive to irrelevant image features (hospital equipment in X-rays). Adversarial patches cause stop sign misclassification. Small character perturbations dramatically alter NLP predictions. These failure modes exploit **statistical rather than semantic** representations.`,kt:["Adversarial Attacks","Distribution Shift","Catastrophic Forgetting","Trust Deficit"]},
{id:"6.2",t:"How Symbolic Constraints Improve Robustness",c:`Neuro-symbolic approaches impose symbolic constraints that outputs **must satisfy regardless of input perturbations**. If constrained by "a patient cannot have both type 1 and type 2 diabetes simultaneously," no adversarial perturbation produces violating output — a **hard guarantee** independent of neural vulnerability.\n\nA 2025 survey (Arabian JSER) reviewed three dimensions:\n\n**Robustness** — Logical constraints bound the output space, preventing adversarial manipulation from producing impossible or contradictory outputs.\n\n**Uncertainty Quantification** — Probabilistic logic provides calibrated uncertainty estimates grounded in formal semantics, rather than ad hoc neural uncertainty (MC dropout, deep ensembles).\n\n**Intervenability** — Explicit rule representation allows human operators to modify behavior by changing rules without retraining. Essential for regulatory compliance and iterative improvement.`,kt:["Hard Guarantees","Symbolic Constraints","Inductive Bias","Intervenability"],dg:"robustness"},
{id:"6.3",t:"Neuro-Symbolic Uncertainty Quantification",c:`**Probabilistic neuro-symbolic systems** (DeepProbLog, probabilistic logic programming) provide principled mechanisms combining calibration properties of probabilistic logic with representational power of neural networks. The probabilistic logic program specifies the logical structure of uncertainty propagation; neural networks provide input probabilities. Resulting estimates are grounded in well-defined **probabilistic semantics**, contrasting with ad hoc neural uncertainty.\n\nThis is critical for healthcare: a system that says "I am 73% confident in this diagnosis, with uncertainty concentrated on these differential diagnoses" provides vastly more useful clinical information than a black-box confidence score.`,kt:["Probabilistic Semantics","Calibrated Uncertainty","DeepProbLog","Clinical Decision Making"]},
{id:"6.4",t:"Explainability and Intervenability",c:`**Explainability** is perhaps the single most compelling advantage. Because symbolic components use explicit, human-readable representations and rules, reasoning is **inherently transparent**. A neuro-symbolic system provides traces showing which rules applied, which facts were used, and how conclusions were derived — a **genuine explanation** rather than post-hoc approximation.\n\n**Intervenability** — modifying behavior by changing knowledge or rules — is a related advantage. If a medical diagnosis system produces incorrect output because of a wrong rule, the rule can be identified and corrected without retraining. This contrasts with neural networks where correcting specific behavior requires retraining with modified data, with no guarantee the correction won't introduce new errors.`,kt:["Reasoning Traces","Explainability","Intervenability","Transparent Reasoning"],ins:"For healthcare: calibrated uncertainty (knowing when unsure) + genuine explainability (knowing why) addresses both primary barriers to clinical AI adoption."},
{id:"6.5",t:"Verification, Validation, and Safety",c:`Neuro-symbolic systems benefit from formal verification: **model checking**, **theorem proving**, **constraint satisfaction**. The symbolic component can be formally verified to satisfy safety properties — e.g., an autonomous vehicle's planning module never generates plans violating traffic rules.\n\nWhile neural components are harder to verify formally, symbolic constraints provide an additional **safety layer** bounding neural outputs within a **verified envelope**. Renkhoff et al. (2024) identified this layered verification as the most promising path toward **certifiable neuro-symbolic systems** for safety-critical applications.\n\nThe verification challenge is fundamentally different from verifying either component alone: ensuring symbolic guard rails properly constrain neural outputs, that neural components don't "work around" symbolic constraints, and that the system as a whole satisfies safety properties — requires new verification methodologies still being developed.`,kt:["Formal Verification","Safety Envelope","Certifiable AI","Model Checking","Layered Verification"]}
],rf:["Arabian JSER (2025). NeSy for robustness, UQ, intervenability.","Garcez & Lamb (2023). NeSy AI: The 3rd wave. AI Review, 56.","Guo et al. (2017). On calibration of modern NNs. ICML.","Renkhoff et al. (2024). VV&T of NeSy AI. arXiv."]},

{id:"ch7",n:7,t:"Applications Across Domains",ic:"VII",cl:"#0284c7",ss:[
{id:"7.1",t:"Healthcare and Medical Diagnosis",c:`Medical diagnosis requires both **perceptual processing** (images, clinical text) and **structured reasoning** (diagnostic criteria, differentials, medical ontologies). Purely neural approaches achieve impressive pattern recognition but lack structured reasoning and explainability required for **clinical trust and regulatory compliance**.\n\nLNN-based **diabetes prediction** (2024) outperformed RF and SVM while providing transparent, auditable reasoning. **DR.KNOWS** grounds LLM diagnostics in **UMLS/SNOMED CT** knowledge graphs, reducing hallucination.\n\nFor **rural healthcare**: neuro-symbolic CDS could bring specialist-level reasoning to settings lacking specialists, while the symbolic component ensures generalist providers can understand and critically evaluate recommendations. This is particularly significant for **Critical Access Hospitals** and **Rural Emergency Hospitals** where specialist consultation may be hours away.`,kt:["Clinical Decision Support","UMLS","SNOMED CT","Rural Healthcare","LNN Diagnosis","Critical Access Hospitals"],ins:"For rural Critical Access Hospitals, neuro-symbolic CDS offers unique value: neural handles pattern recognition across rare conditions while symbolic ensures recommendations are grounded in verifiable clinical guidelines."},
{id:"7.2",t:"Autonomous Systems and Robotics",c:`Autonomous vehicles and robots must make real-time decisions in complex, dynamic environments while satisfying safety constraints. Neuro-symbolic architectures combine **neural perception** (camera, lidar, radar) with **symbolic planning and constraint satisfaction** (traffic rules, mission plans, collision avoidance).\n\nAmazon reportedly applied NeSy approaches in 2025 to **Vulcan warehouse robots** and **Rufus shopping assistant**, using symbolic constraints to enforce accuracy that pure neural systems could not guarantee. Even in well-controlled environments, pure neural systems make errors that are commercially and physically unacceptable — errors symbolic constraints prevent.\n\nThe architectural pattern typically follows Kautz's **Type 2** (Symbolic[Neuro]): a symbolic planning engine provides the overall decision framework, with neural networks providing perception subroutines.`,kt:["Autonomous Vehicles","Symbolic Planning","Safety Constraints","Vulcan Robots","Rufus","Type 2 Architecture"]},
{id:"7.3",t:"Mathematics and Scientific Reasoning",c:`AlphaGeometry demonstrated neuro-symbolic approaches can tackle **advanced mathematical reasoning** — its architecture (neural LM guiding symbolic deduction) templates scientific reasoning requiring creative hypothesis generation + rigorous verification.\n\nExtensions to other mathematical domains, physics simulation, and scientific discovery are active research. The general pattern — neural generates candidates, symbolic verifies correctness and prunes search — applies wherever the search space is too large for pure symbolic and correctness criteria too rigorous for pure neural.\n\nImplications for **drug discovery** (propose molecules, verify validity), **materials science** (predict properties, simulate verification), and **theorem proving** (suggest strategies, formally verify).`,kt:["AlphaGeometry","Scientific Discovery","Drug Discovery","Materials Science","Theorem Proving"]},
{id:"7.4",t:"Natural Language Understanding and Question Answering",c:`**Visual question answering** has been a primary NeSy testbed. NSCL and successors demonstrated combining neural perception with symbolic program execution achieves superior **compositional generalization** on CLEVR and GQA benchmarks.\n\nFor NLI, neuro-symbolic approaches combining neural language understanding with logical constraint checking improved multi-step reasoning. The NeSy generative model augmenting GPT-NeoX achieved **93.1% logical reasoning accuracy** — concrete demonstration that symbolic components substantially improve LLM capabilities.`,kt:["VQA","CLEVR","GQA","Compositional Generalization","93.1% Accuracy"]},
{id:"7.5",t:"Cybersecurity and Anomaly Detection",c:`Cybersecurity requires both pattern recognition (detecting anomalous traffic, identifying malware) and rule-based reasoning (applying security policies, tracing attack chains, ensuring compliance). Neuro-symbolic systems provide a **"traceable path"** for critical, auditable security decisions — required in regulated industries.\n\nIntegrating neural anomaly detection with symbolic rule engines enables systems that both **detect novel threats** and **explain why** they flagged specific events — essential for incident response and regulatory reporting.`,kt:["Cybersecurity","Anomaly Detection","Auditable Decisions","Traceable Reasoning"]}
],rf:["Hossain et al. (2025). NeSy AI in healthcare. arXiv.","Mao et al. (2019). NSCL. ICLR.","Piplai et al. (2023). NeSy for cybersecurity. AI Comms.","Trinh et al. (2024). AlphaGeometry. Nature, 625."]},

{id:"ch8",n:8,t:"Open Problems & Future Directions",ic:"VIII",cl:"#7c3aed",ss:[
{id:"8.1",t:"The Scalability Bottleneck",c:`The most significant technical barrier: symbolic reasoning grows **combinatorially** with knowledge base size and reasoning depth. Neural networks scale efficiently via GPU parallelism; symbolic engines are often sequential and memory-intensive.\n\nPromising directions: **approximate inference**, **neural compilation** (training NNs to approximate symbolic reasoning for common cases, falling back to exact symbolic for edge cases), and **hardware acceleration** of symbolic operations. Scallop's provenance semirings and DeepLog's algebraic circuits represent steps, but achieving the scale of modern LLMs remains open.\n\nThe "fast path / slow path" neural compilation architecture mirrors the System 1/System 2 metaphor at a micro level — potentially offering practical scalability.`,kt:["Scalability","Combinatorial Explosion","Approximate Inference","Neural Compilation"]},
{id:"8.2",t:"The Knowledge Engineering Bottleneck",c:`Most successful NeSy systems rely on **hand-engineered symbolic knowledge** — rules, ontologies, knowledge bases created by domain experts. The most successful systems (AlphaGeometry, LLM-SS) are loosely-coupled hybrids whose components are trained separately because joint learning is "exceedingly difficult."\n\n**Chicken-and-egg problem**: neural needs accurate rules for training signal; rules need accurate neural predictions to be learned. Solving this **joint learning problem** — end-to-end acquisition of both neural representations and symbolic knowledge from raw data — remains a grand challenge.\n\n**Abductive learning** is promising: using abductive reasoning (inference to the best explanation) to simultaneously learn symbolic rules and neural representations from partially labeled data.`,kt:["Knowledge Engineering","Joint Learning","End-to-End Acquisition","Abductive Learning"]},
{id:"8.3",t:"Meta-Cognition: The Unexplored Frontier",c:`Only **5% of papers** address meta-cognition — the system's capacity to monitor, evaluate, and adjust its own reasoning:\n\n**Self-awareness** — knowing what the system knows and doesn't know. A meta-cognitive system would identify knowledge gaps and request additional information or defer to human expertise.\n\n**Adaptive learning** — adjusting learning strategies based on performance, rather than following fixed training procedures.\n\n**Reflective reasoning** — evaluating inference quality before outputting conclusions, assessing strength of reasoning chains and reliability of evidence.\n\n**Self-regulation** — modifying behavior based on self-assessment. If recent predictions have been unreliable, automatically increase confidence thresholds or activate more thorough reasoning.\n\nEssential for AI operating reliably in **open-ended, unpredictable environments** where problem distributions cannot be anticipated at training time.`,kt:["Meta-Cognition","Self-Awareness","Reflective Reasoning","Adaptive Learning","Self-Regulation"],dg:"metacognition"},
{id:"8.4",t:"Standardization and Benchmarking",c:`The field lacks **standardized benchmarks**, integration frameworks, and evaluation metrics. Different systems are evaluated on different tasks, making systematic comparison difficult. Comprehensive benchmark suites — testing compositionality, counterfactual reasoning, systematic generalization, cognitive-level collaboration — are essential.\n\nThe **NeSy Frameworks comparison project**, evaluating DeepProbLog, Scallop, and others on identical tasks with identical metrics, represents an important step toward standardization.`,kt:["Benchmarking","Standardization","NeSy Frameworks","Evaluation Metrics"]},
{id:"8.5",t:"The Path to Artificial General Intelligence",c:`Neuro-symbolic AI is at the heart of the modern **AGI debate**. Marcus argues AGI is impossible without "hybrid architecture, rich prior knowledge, and sophisticated reasoning." AlphaGeometry provides concrete evidence that principled neuro-symbolic integration achieves capabilities neither paradigm achieves alone.\n\nWhether AGI requires **explicit symbolic engineering** or will **emerge from sufficient neural scale** remains open — but the pragmatic consensus moves toward architectures that explicitly combine both, leveraging strengths of each to compensate for limitations of the other.`,kt:["AGI","Marcus Triumvirate","Emergence","Explicit Engineering"]}
],rf:["Colelough & Regli (2025). Systematic review. arXiv:2501.05435.","Garcez & Lamb (2023). NeSy AI: 3rd wave. AI Review, 56.","Marcus (2020). Next decade in AI. arXiv:2002.06177.","Sheth et al. (2023). NeSy AI — Why, what, how. arXiv."]},

{id:"glossary",n:9,t:"Glossary & Bibliography",ic:"⟐",cl:"#64748b",ss:[{id:"glo",t:"Key Terms & Comprehensive Bibliography",c:`**Abductive Learning** — Integrating ML and logical reasoning through inference to the best explanation, enabling mutual improvement.\n\n**Algebraic Circuit** — Computational graph over a chosen semiring; backend for probabilistic/logical reasoning in systems like DeepProbLog.\n\n**d-DNNF** — Deterministic Decomposable Negation Normal Form; canonical form for Boolean circuits enabling efficient probabilistic inference.\n\n**DeepProbLog** — Probabilistic logic programming with neural predicates for end-to-end differentiable integration.\n\n**Differentiable Logic** — Smooth approximations of discrete logic enabling gradient-based optimization while preserving semantic properties.\n\n**Dual-Process Theory** — Kahneman's System 1 (fast, intuitive) / System 2 (slow, deliberate) framework — the organizing metaphor for NeSy design.\n\n**Fuzzy Logic** — Truth values in [0, 1]; continuous relaxation for differentiable computation.\n\n**Knowledge Engineering Bottleneck** — Difficulty of encoding expert knowledge in symbolic form.\n\n**LTN (Logic Tensor Network)** — Grounds first-order logic in neural tensors using fuzzy semantics.\n\n**LNN (Logical Neural Network)** — IBM architecture where every neuron = a logical component. Bidirectional reasoning.\n\n**Meta-Cognition** — System monitoring/adjusting its own reasoning. Least explored (5%).\n\n**Neural Predicate** — Predicate whose truth value comes from a neural network.\n\n**NTP (Neural Theorem Prover)** — Differentiable networks from AND-OR proof trees.\n\n**NeSy** — Neuro-Symbolic AI. "The Third Wave."\n\n**NSCL** — Neuro-Symbolic Concept Learner. MIT-IBM: neural perception + symbolic execution for VQA.\n\n**Provenance Semiring** — Algebraic structure tracking derivation paths; enables differentiable reasoning.\n\n**Scallop** — Scalable NeSy language: Datalog with provenance semirings.\n\n**Semantic Loss** — Loss penalizing neural outputs violating logical constraints.\n\n**t-norm** — Binary operation on [0, 1] for fuzzy conjunction. Product, Gödel, Łukasiewicz.\n\n---\n\n**Comprehensive Bibliography**\n\nBadreddine, S. et al. (2022). Logic Tensor Networks. AI, 303, 103649.\nBengio, Y. (2019). System 1→System 2 deep learning. NeurIPS Keynote.\nChen, M. K. (2025). Comparative study. PMLR 284. NeSy@IJCAI.\nColelough, B. & Regli, W. (2025). Systematic review. arXiv:2501.05435.\nDe Raedt, L. et al. (2007). ProbLog. IJCAI.\nDerkinderen, V. et al. (2025). DeepLog Machine. arXiv:2508.13697.\nFang, M. et al. (2024). LLMs as NeSy reasoners. AAAI. arXiv:2401.09334.\nGao, Y. et al. (2025). KG-augmented LLMs. JMIR AI, 4, e58670.\nGarcez, A. d. & Lamb, L. C. (2023). NeSy: 3rd wave. AI Review, 56.\nGarcez, A. d. et al. (2015). NeSy learning: Contributions/challenges. AAAI.\nGarcez, A. d. et al. (2002). Neural-Symbolic Learning Systems. Springer.\nGuo, C. et al. (2017). Calibration of modern NNs. ICML.\nHochreiter, S. & Schmidhuber, J. (1997). LSTM. Neural Comp., 9(8).\nKahneman, D. (2011). Thinking, Fast and Slow. FSG.\nKautz, H. (2020). Third AI summer. AAAI Engelmore Lecture.\nLeCun, Y. et al. (1998). Gradient-based learning. Proc. IEEE, 86(11).\nLi, Z. et al. (2023). Scallop. PLDI.\nManhaeve, R. et al. (2018). DeepProbLog. NeurIPS.\nMao, J. et al. (2019). NSCL. ICLR.\nMarcus, G. (2020). Next decade in AI. arXiv:2002.06177.\nMarcus, G. & Davis, E. (2019). Rebooting AI. Pantheon.\nPan, S. et al. (2024). Unifying LLMs and KGs. IEEE TKDE, 36(7).\nPatil, R. & Jadon, S. (2025). NeSy generative AI. IJSRA, 16(01).\nRenkhoff, J. et al. (2024). VV&T of NeSy AI. arXiv.\nRiegel, R. et al. (2020). LNN. arXiv:2006.13155.\nRocktäschel, T. & Riedel, S. (2017). Differentiable proving. NeurIPS.\nSutton, R. (2019). The bitter lesson.\nTrinh, T. H. et al. (2024). AlphaGeometry. Nature, 625, 476–482.\nVaswani, A. et al. (2017). Attention is all you need. NeurIPS.\nXu, J. et al. (2018). Semantic loss. ICML.`}]}
];

const QZ=[
{q:"What type in Kautz's taxonomy represents full System 1/System 2 integration?",o:["Type 2","Type 4","Type 6","Type 3"],a:2,x:"Type 6 (Neuro ↔ Symbolic) features tightly coupled bidirectional feedback — the most ambitious pattern."},
{q:"What percentage of papers in the 2025 systematic review addressed meta-cognition?",o:["28%","35%","5%","63%"],a:2,x:"Meta-cognition: only 5% of papers, yet a critical frontier for self-aware AI systems."},
{q:"Which system solved IMO-level geometry problems?",o:["DeepProbLog","NSCL","AlphaGeometry","Scallop"],a:2,x:"AlphaGeometry (Nature 2024) combined symbolic deduction with a neural LM trained on 100M synthetic pairs."},
{q:"What does a t-norm implement in fuzzy logic?",o:["Disjunction","Conjunction","Negation","Implication"],a:1,x:"t-norms implement conjunction (AND). Product, Gödel, Łukasiewicz each induce different gradient behavior."},
{q:"What accuracy did the neuro-symbolic GPT-NeoX hybrid achieve?",o:["79.5%","88.7%","93.1%","91.2%"],a:2,x:"93.1% logical reasoning accuracy, surpassing GPT-3 (79.5%) and SymbolicGPT (88.7%)."},
{q:"What is the 'bitter lesson' (Sutton, 2019)?",o:["Symbolic AI always wins","Scale and compute beat hand-crafted knowledge","Hybrid systems are unnecessary","Data is irrelevant"],a:1,x:"Sutton argued methods leveraging massive computation historically outperform human-crafted knowledge."},
{q:"What makes LNNs unique among neuro-symbolic systems?",o:["Fuzzy logic","Bidirectional reasoning","Speed","No training needed"],a:1,x:"LNNs uniquely perform both upward (premises→conclusion) and downward (conclusion→required premises) inference."},
{q:"Which approach is architecturally non-invasive?",o:["LTN","DeepProbLog","Semantic Loss","LNN"],a:2,x:"Semantic loss only modifies the training loss — the neural architecture remains unchanged."},
{q:"How many synthetic pairs trained AlphaGeometry's neural model?",o:["1 million","10 million","100 million","1 billion"],a:2,x:"100 million synthetic theorem-proof pairs — the symbolic engine generated the training data."},
{q:"What is NSCL's key advantage over end-to-end neural models?",o:["Speed","10× sample efficiency","Adversarial robustness","No rules needed"],a:1,x:"NSCL maintains accuracy with ~10% of the data end-to-end models require, via compositional symbolic structure."},
{q:"What is a 'neural predicate' in DeepProbLog?",o:["A hand-coded rule","A predicate whose truth value comes from a neural network","A loss function","A knowledge graph node"],a:1,x:"Neural predicates bridge the neural-symbolic gap: their truth values are neural network outputs fed into logical programs."},
{q:"What compilation target enables DeepProbLog's gradient computation?",o:["LLVM IR","d-DNNF algebraic circuits","WebAssembly","CUDA kernels"],a:1,x:"d-DNNF (Deterministic Decomposable Negation Normal Form) enables efficient probabilistic inference and gradient computation."},
{q:"Which knowledge graph system grounds LLM diagnostic reasoning?",o:["DR.KNOWS","AlphaGeometry","Scallop","NSCL"],a:0,x:"DR.KNOWS retrieves contextually relevant paths from UMLS-based knowledge graphs to augment LLM diagnostics."},
{q:"What are the three pillars of NeSy trustworthiness?",o:["Speed, accuracy, scale","Robustness, uncertainty, intervenability","Learning, reasoning, meta-cognition","Perception, planning, execution"],a:1,x:"The 2025 Arabian JSER survey identified robustness, uncertainty quantification, and intervenability as the three pillars."},
{q:"What does the DeepLog Machine unify?",o:["Different LLM architectures","Multiple NeSy frameworks via algebraic structures","Neural network layers","Training datasets"],a:1,x:"The DeepLog Machine uses algebraic structures (Boolean, probabilistic, fuzzy) to express multiple NeSy frameworks in a common language."}
];

// ─── DIAGRAMS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
function KautzDiagram({T}){const ty=[{l:"Type 1",d:"Neural replaces Symbolic",c:10,ex:"Neural NLP Parser",a:"S→N"},{l:"Type 2",d:"Symbolic[Neuro]",c:30,ex:"AlphaGo",a:"S[N]"},{l:"Type 3",d:"Neuro|Symbolic",c:45,ex:"Knowledge Distillation",a:"N|S"},{l:"Type 4",d:"Symbolic→Neuro data",c:60,ex:"AlphaGeometry Training",a:"S→N"},{l:"Type 5",d:"Neuro[Symbolic]",c:80,ex:"LTN, NTP, LNN",a:"N[S]"},{l:"Type 6",d:"Neuro↔Symbolic",c:100,ex:"Full Dual-Process",a:"N↔S"}];const[h,sH]=useState(null);return(<div style={{background:T.ab,borderRadius:14,padding:20,margin:"18px 0",border:`1px solid ${T.bd}`}}><div style={{fontSize:15,fontWeight:700,marginBottom:12,color:T.ac,fontFamily:"'Cormorant Garamond',serif"}}>Kautz's Taxonomy — Loose → Tight Coupling</div>{ty.map((t,i)=>(<div key={i} onMouseEnter={()=>sH(i)} onMouseLeave={()=>sH(null)} style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:8,padding:"6px 10px",borderRadius:6,background:h===i?`${T.ac}12`:T.sf,transition:"all 0.2s",cursor:"pointer",marginBottom:3}}><div style={{fontWeight:700,fontSize:11,color:T.ac,minWidth:44,fontFamily:"monospace"}}>{t.l}</div><div style={{fontFamily:"monospace",fontSize:9,color:T.tm,minWidth:24}}>{t.a}</div><div style={{flex:1,height:5,borderRadius:3,background:T.bd,overflow:"hidden"}}><div style={{height:"100%",borderRadius:3,width:`${t.c}%`,background:T.ac,transition:"width 0.5s"}}/></div><div style={{fontSize:10,color:T.tm,minWidth:140,textAlign:"right",fontFamily:"system-ui"}}>{h===i?<span style={{color:T.ac,fontWeight:600}}>{t.ex}</span>:t.d}</div></div>))}<div style={{display:"flex",justifyContent:"space-between",marginTop:6,fontSize:9,color:T.tm,fontStyle:"italic"}}><span>← Loose</span><span>Tight →</span></div></div>);}

function ResearchAreasDiagram({T}){const d=[{a:"Learning & Inference",p:63,n:105},{a:"Knowledge Rep.",p:44,n:73},{a:"Logic & Reasoning",p:35,n:58},{a:"Explainability",p:28,n:47},{a:"Meta-Cognition",p:5,n:8}];return(<div style={{background:T.ab,borderRadius:14,padding:20,margin:"18px 0",border:`1px solid ${T.bd}`}}><div style={{fontSize:15,fontWeight:700,marginBottom:12,color:T.ac,fontFamily:"'Cormorant Garamond',serif"}}>2025 Systematic Review — 167 Papers</div>{d.map((x,i)=>(<div key={i} style={{display:"flex",alignItems:"center",gap:8,marginBottom:6}}><div style={{fontSize:11,minWidth:105,color:T.tx,fontWeight:500,fontFamily:"system-ui"}}>{x.a}</div><div style={{flex:1,height:18,background:T.sa,borderRadius:4,overflow:"hidden"}}><div style={{height:"100%",borderRadius:4,background:T.ac,width:`${x.p}%`,display:"flex",alignItems:"center",justifyContent:"flex-end",paddingRight:5,transition:"width 1s"}}>{x.p>12&&<span style={{color:"#fff",fontSize:9,fontWeight:700}}>{x.p}%</span>}</div></div><div style={{fontSize:9,color:T.tm,minWidth:36,fontFamily:"monospace"}}>~{x.n}</div></div>))}</div>);}

